function secondMinimum(n, edges, time, change) {
    const adj = new Array(n + 1).fill(null).map(() => []);
    for (const [u, v] of edges) {
        adj[u].push(v);
        adj[v].push(u);
    }

    const dist = new Array(n + 1).fill(-1);
    const queue = [[0, 1]];
    dist[1] = 0;

    while (queue.length > 0) {
        queue.sort((a, b) => a[0] - b[0]);
        const [t1, v1] = queue.shift();

        if (v1 === n) {
            return t1;
        }

        for (const v2 of adj[v1]) {
            const t2 = t1 + time;
            const waiting = (t2 / change) % 2 === 1 ? change - (t2 % change) : 0;

            if (dist[v2] === -1 || dist[v2] > t2 + waiting) {
                if (dist[v2] !== -1) {
                    queue.push([dist[v2], v2]);
                }
                dist[v2] = t2 + waiting;
                queue.push([dist[v2], v2]);
            }
        }
    }

    return -1;
}
```

    The algorithm uses Dijkstra's shortest path algorithm with some modifications to take into account the waiting time at the vertices due to the traffic signal. It maintains a priority queue to store the vertices sorted by time taken to reach a vertex (including waiting time). We start from vertex 1 with time 0.

For each vertex, we iterate over its neighbors and calculate the time taken to reach the neighbor, adjusted for waiting. If this time is less than the previously calculated time (or the neighbor has not been visited yet), we update the time and push the old distance to the queue.

When we reach vertex n, we will have found our second minimum time as we have now encountered the vertex twice.

The time complexity of this algorithm is O(nlogn + m), where n is the number of vertices and m is the number of edges.

